ll been evacuated by officials of Lagos State Emergency Management Agency, LASEMA, from the road, placed on a layby and handed over to members of the Nigerian Police Force present at the incident scene. The multiple accidents also left the towed Sienna damaged beyond recognition after the two units of 20feet containers fell off the articulated truck conveying them, onto the other vehicles on the impact of the crash, then eventual recovery of all vehicles involved, utilising LASEMA’s heavy-duty equipment (Crane), to set the road free for vehicular activities. According to Director-General, LASEMA, Dr Femi Oke-Osanyintolu, “Preliminary report gathered at the scene of the incident revealed an accident which involved a truck with registration number APP 444 XV conveying twin 20fts containers and a Toyota Sienna Bus with registration number SMK 22 AV which is being towed by a private towing truck with an unknown registration number. “Further investigations revealed that the tow truck broke down along the above-mentioned corridor and efforts were being made by the operators to fix it before the truck which was on top speed suddenly developed brake failure and rammed into the tow truck and the towed vehicle. “Unfortunately, the two containers fell off the truck and landed on the Toyota Sienna and the tow truck, killing the truck assistant of the truck at the spot and damaged the Sienna beyond recognition. “However, the commodity has been evacuated by the Nigerian Police, Ijesha division before the arrival of LASEMA Response Team.” Vanguard A tanker driver and his conductor were Monday evening burnt to death as their 33, 000 litres capacity diesel laden truck went up in flames at Cele-bus stop inward Oshodi in Lagos. July 25, 2016 In "News" LAGOS—A tanker driver and his conductor were, yesterday evening, roasted to death as their 33,000-litre capacity diesel laden truck went up in flames at Cele Bus Stop, inward Oshodi, on Apapa-Oshodi Expressway, Lagos. July 26, 2016 In "News" For two days running, vehicular movement in most parts of the state have been grounded, with commercial activities paralysed. No thanks to the chaotic gridlock which seemed to have overwhelmed government agencies saddled with the responsibility of controlling the free flow of traffic. September 23, 2015 In "News"